content: I used it but now I use it as a backup from my new password manager
Trust

The app works great, but with over 300 accounts and different passwords I was getting a little nervous and wanted to back everything up. First of all, Petr is VERY responsive. Unfortunately, I'm into my second day of trying to back up my files with no luck. I'm going to have to copy them over by hand, I have no other option. If you don't intend to back up your files, I think it's great and have used it for years, if you do intend to back your passwords up, I would use caution. I still have not been able to retrieve any of my data. I can see the data.crypt file Petr is talking about, he even looked at it and said it looks fine, but every time I try to restore my passwords, it say "Download Failed." I have two Google accounts and have tried both of those and once I logged into those I checked for the data,crypt files in both Google Drive and Drop Box and used the only one I found in all of those, still nothing. Although Petr has been very responsive, it hasn't helped me in the end. I'm very disappointed in the ability to retrieve my information and I would suggest if you're going to use aWallet you also back up your passwords somewhere else, which negates the whole purpose of the aWallet, to securely protect your passwords with the ability to restore them from the cloud if your phone is lost, as was mine.
replyContent: Hello Dayton, If the data.crypt is not found in the cloud then either wrong cloud was chosen or aWallet Cloud doesn't have permission to read it. The permission may not be granted in the case when the data.crypt file was created manually by the user and not by the app itself. aWallet Cloud can only access files it created itself in the cloud.

content: Pro: Saves your passwords, makes passwords if you need & backs up encrypted to your cloud... (BIG) Con: BUT also requests permission to see your contact list. Now I've been using this app for years and can't find any reason to need access to my contacts. Lose major stars for privacy awallet.. Bummer cause I loved you so... 💔 (womp-womp)
replyContent: Hello Jason, The Contacts/Accounts permission is needed for Google Drive synchronization to find out Google accounts added in the Android Settings / Accounts. aWallet Cloud doesn't have access to your contacts but only to your own accounts stored in Android Settings. If you are concerned about it switch to Dropbox cloud which doesn't need it.

To select/change cloud:

2. Press the menu button on the home screen
3. Choose Settings / Cloud
4. Select the cloud (Google Drive or Dropbox)
5. Choose your cloud user account
The data.crypt file backup will be located in the selected cloud account.

replyContent: Hello Pradip, Thanks for your review. Typical Category has about 4-6 fields (e.g. Name, Password, Web Site, Note) per Category. I hope 25 fields limit is already big enough. aWallet is a password manager. It is not meant to be used as general purpose database. These limits are there to avoid importing too much data from CSV files.
